  <content>
    <title>LangChain RAG Pipeline</title>

    <summary>A LangChain RAG pipeline loads documents via loaders, splits them with RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter, embeds them into a vectorstore (Chroma or Pinecone), then wraps the retriever in an LCEL chain: context retriever branch runs in parallel with the question passthrough, feeds into a prompt, then an LLM, then a parser.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>LangChain's modular design lets each RAG stage (load, split, embed, retrieve, generate) be swapped independently. LCEL's pipe syntax keeps the chain topology declarative and readable, while the retriever abstraction hides whether the backend is Chroma, Pinecone, or any other vectorstore. This is the canonical pattern for grounded generation when the knowledge base is too large to fit in a prompt.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <p>Apply this methodology when the agent must build a question-answering system over a private corpus that exceeds the model context window, AND provider/vectorstore swap-ability is a real requirement.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Building LLM applications that must answer questions from a private document corpus.</item>
        <item>Rapid prototyping of RAG pipelines where provider flexibility (OpenAI, Anthropic) is required without rewriting the retrieval chain.</item>
        <item>Projects that need composable, swappable retrieval components (prompt templates, parsers, retrievers).</item>
        <item>Implementing RAG pipelines where documents must be loaded, split, embedded, and retrieved.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Simple single-call LLM tasks — LCEL pipe syntax adds complexity with no benefit over a direct API call.</item>
        <item>When you control the model exclusively (Claude-only) — the Anthropic SDK directly is simpler and cheaper.</item>
        <item>When avoiding dependency bloat: langchain + langchain-openai + langchain-community adds ~200 transitive dependencies.</item>
        <item>Projects with strict latency SLAs where LCEL's serialization overhead matters.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <how-to>
      <p>Execute these steps in order. Do not skip stages — each later stage depends on artifacts produced earlier.</p>
      <step>Install pinned dependencies (see commands block) and confirm Python ≥3.10. Set <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[OPENAI_API_KEY]]></code> in the environment.</step>
      <step>Choose loaders matching the source: <code lang="text"><![CDATA[TextLoader]]></code> for plain text, <code lang="text"><![CDATA[PyPDFLoader]]></code> for PDF, <code lang="text"><![CDATA[WebBaseLoader]]></code> for HTML, <code lang="text"><![CDATA[DirectoryLoader]]></code> for batch ingestion. Wrap imports in try/except ImportError.</step>
      <step>Configure <code lang="text"><![CDATA[RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter]]></code> with <code lang="text"><![CDATA[chunk_size=1000]]></code> and <code lang="text"><![CDATA[chunk_overlap=200]]></code> as defaults; tune only after measuring retrieval recall.</step>
      <step>Pick an embeddings model (<code lang="text"><![CDATA[text-embedding-3-small]]></code> for cost; <code lang="text"><![CDATA[text-embedding-3-large]]></code> for quality) and persist the vectorstore on disk with <code lang="text"><![CDATA[persist_directory]]></code> so re-runs do not re-embed.</step>
      <step>Build the LCEL chain: parallel dict {<code lang="text"><![CDATA[context]]></code>: retriever | format_docs, <code lang="text"><![CDATA[question]]></code>: RunnablePassthrough()} | prompt | llm | StrOutputParser().</step>
      <step>Smoke-test with at least 3 questions whose answers exist verbatim in the corpus, then run the verify checklist below.</step>
    </how-to>

    <commands>
      <command name="install"><![CDATA[pip install "langchain==0.3.*" "langchain-openai==0.2.*" "langchain-community==0.3.*" "langchain-text-splitters==0.3.*" "langchain-chroma==0.1.*" "chromadb>=0.5,<0.6" pypdf]]></command>
      <command name="env-check"><![CDATA[python -c "import langchain, langchain_openai, langchain_chroma; print(langchain.__version__)"]]></command>
      <command name="set-key"><![CDATA[export OPENAI_API_KEY="sk-..."]]></command>
      <command name="run-pipeline"><![CDATA[python rag_pipeline.py]]></command>
      <command name="inspect-store"><![CDATA[python -c "from langchain_chroma import Chroma; from langchain_openai import OpenAIEmbeddings; vs=Chroma(persist_directory='./chroma_db', embedding_function=OpenAIEmbeddings(model='text-embedding-3-small')); print(vs._collection.count())"]]></command>
    </commands>

    <section name="document-loading">
      <p>LangChain ships loaders for text files, PDFs, web pages, and entire directories. The DirectoryLoader accepts a glob pattern and a loader class, applying it uniformly across all matched files.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Always add explicit try/except ImportError guards around langchain-community loaders (WebBaseLoader, PyPDFLoader); they depend on external libraries that may not be installed.</statement>
        <rationale>langchain-community loaders are maintained by contributors, not LangChain core; quality varies and missing optional deps silently break pipelines.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Loading documents from multiple sources">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from langchain_community.document_loaders import (
    TextLoader,
    PyPDFLoader,
    WebBaseLoader,
    DirectoryLoader
)

# Load a single PDF
pdf_loader = PyPDFLoader("document.pdf")

# Load all .txt files in a directory
dir_loader = DirectoryLoader(
    "./documents",
    glob="**/*.txt",
    loader_cls=TextLoader
)
documents = dir_loader.load()
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="text-splitting">
      <p>RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter is the standard choice: it tries to split on paragraph breaks, then newlines, then spaces, then characters, preserving semantic units as long as possible within the chunk_size budget.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use chunk_overlap of at least 10-20% of chunk_size so that sentences that span chunk boundaries appear in both chunks and are not lost from retrieval.</statement>
        <rationale>Without overlap, a sentence split across a boundary may not appear in either chunk's embedding space, causing retrieval misses for queries that match that sentence.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Splitting with overlap and metadata tagging">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from langchain_text_splitters import RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter

text_splitter = RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter(
    chunk_size=1000,
    chunk_overlap=200,
    length_function=len,
    separators=["\n\n", "\n", " ", ""]
)

splits = text_splitter.split_documents(documents)

# Tag each chunk with its position
for i, split in enumerate(splits):
    split.metadata["chunk_id"] = i
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="vectorstore-and-retriever">
      <p>Chroma is the default local vectorstore for prototyping. It requires no server; the index is persisted to disk. For production, swap to Pinecone or a managed service without changing the retriever interface.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Embedding documents into Chroma">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from langchain_openai import OpenAIEmbeddings
from langchain_chroma import Chroma
from langchain_core.documents import Document

embeddings = OpenAIEmbeddings(model="text-embedding-3-small")

documents = [
    Document(page_content="LangChain is a framework for LLM apps", metadata={"source": "docs"}),
    Document(page_content="LCEL is the expression language for chains", metadata={"source": "docs"}),
]

vectorstore = Chroma.from_documents(
    documents=documents,
    embedding=embeddings,
    persist_directory="./chroma_db",
)

# Retrieve top-3 most similar chunks
retriever = vectorstore.as_retriever(search_kwargs={"k": 3})
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="rag-lcel-chain">
      <p>The canonical RAG chain feeds the retriever output and the raw question into a prompt via RunnablePassthrough and a parallel dict assignment. The retriever branch formats each retrieved Document's page_content before injection.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Always define a format_docs helper that joins retrieved Document objects into a plain-text context string before passing to the prompt; never pass the raw Document list.</statement>
        <rationale>ChatPromptTemplate expects string values; passing a list of Document objects causes a silent type coercion that produces malformed context in the prompt.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Full RAG chain with LCEL">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from langchain_openai import ChatOpenAI
from langchain_core.prompts import ChatPromptTemplate
from langchain_core.output_parsers import StrOutputParser
from langchain_core.runnables import RunnablePassthrough

llm = ChatOpenAI(model="gpt-4o", temperature=0)

rag_prompt = ChatPromptTemplate.from_template("""
Answer based on the context below.

Context: {context}

Question: {question}

Answer:""")

def format_docs(docs):
    return "\n\n".join(doc.page_content for doc in docs)

rag_chain = (
    {"context": retriever | format_docs, "question": RunnablePassthrough()}
    | rag_prompt
    | llm
    | StrOutputParser()
)

answer = rag_chain.invoke("What is LangChain?")
]]></code>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Building a RAG chain that passes the raw retriever output (a list of Documents) directly into the prompt template without a format_docs step.</description>
        <reason>The prompt template receives a list object, not a string, causing malformed context and degraded generation quality.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-template">
      <p>This is the canonical grounded-generation prompt. Copy it verbatim, then tighten constraints for your domain.</p>
      <prompt purpose="rag-grounded-answer"><![CDATA[
You are a precise assistant. Answer ONLY using the context below.
If the context does not contain the answer, reply exactly: "I don't know based on the provided context."
Do not invent facts. Quote relevant phrases when helpful.

Context:
{context}

Question: {question}

Answer:
]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <checklist>
      <check>Pinned LangChain versions (0.3.x family) are installed and import without errors.</check>
      <check>Loaders chosen match the corpus type; ImportError guards in place for langchain-community loaders.</check>
      <check>Splitter uses chunk_size=1000 and chunk_overlap≥200 (or documented justification for other values).</check>
      <check>Each chunk carries metadata {source, chunk_id} for downstream filtering and citation.</check>
      <check>Vectorstore uses persist_directory so the embed step is not repeated on each run.</check>
      <check>Retriever k value is set explicitly via search_kwargs (default k=3 for prototyping, k=5-8 for production).</check>
      <check>format_docs helper is present and called via the retriever | format_docs pipe before the prompt.</check>
      <check>LCEL chain ends with StrOutputParser() (or a structured parser) — never returns a raw AIMessage to callers.</check>
      <check>Smoke test with 3+ ground-truth questions returns answers grounded in retrieved context.</check>
      <check>Refusal behavior validated: ask a question whose answer is NOT in the corpus and confirm the model returns the configured refusal string.</check>
    </checklist>

    <verify>
      <step>Run <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[python -c "from langchain_chroma import Chroma; from langchain_openai import OpenAIEmbeddings; vs=Chroma(persist_directory='./chroma_db', embedding_function=OpenAIEmbeddings(model='text-embedding-3-small')); print('chunks:', vs._collection.count())"]]></code> and confirm chunk count is &gt;0 and roughly matches expected (corpus_chars / chunk_size).</step>
      <step>Invoke the retriever directly: <code lang="python"><![CDATA[for d in retriever.invoke("known fact from corpus"): print(d.metadata.get("source"), d.page_content[:120])]]></code>. The top-1 hit must come from the document containing that fact.</step>
      <step>Invoke the full chain on a positive question and assert the answer contains a phrase from the retrieved context (substring overlap &gt;0).</step>
      <step>Invoke the full chain on an out-of-corpus question and assert the answer matches the refusal string defined in the prompt template.</step>
      <step>Inspect intermediate steps with <code lang="python"><![CDATA[rag_chain.invoke("...", config={"callbacks": [ConsoleCallbackHandler()]})]]></code> (or LangSmith) and confirm the prompt rendered with a string context, not a Python list repr.</step>
      <step>Confirm latency budget: time the chain end-to-end; if &gt;3s p50 and that violates SLA, tune k, switch embeddings, or consider dropping LangChain (see when-not-to-use).</step>
    </verify>

    <warning>
      <p>langchain-community is community-maintained. Loaders and integrations there can break across minor versions. Pin transitive deps and add an integration test that loads one document of each source type used in production.</p>
    </warning>

